text:
So im learning python and watching this video https://youtu.be/kqtD5dpn9C8 at around the 40th minute theres an "exercise" with some weight convertion i tried to code it myself where i failed but i dont see any problem then i wrote the code exactly like the guy did and it didnt work the whole exercise is basically about entering your weight in pounds or kg and then typing k for kilograms or l for pounds after that converting lbs to kg, or kg to lbs. Now for me when i try to convert lbs to kg for example i enter 170 lbs then it comes out as 377.7, but for some reason if i input kg to lbs for example  70kg it comes out correctly 155.5 lbs
This is my code:
weight = input("Weight: ")
convertion = input("(K)g or (L)bs: ")
if convertion == "K" or "k":
        lbs_mt = float(weight) / 0.45
        lbs = str(lbs_mt)
        print("You weigh: " + lbs)
elif convertion == "L" or "l":
        kg_mt = float(weight) * 0.45
        kg = str(kg_mt)
        print("You weigh: " + kg)


Now the "answer" that has the same problem but kg to lbs doesnt work for example 70kg is converted to 31.5lbs but lbs to kg works here
weight = int(input("Weight: "))
unit = input ("(K)gs or (L)bs: ")
if unit.upper == "K":
         converted = weight / 0.45
         print("Weight in Lbs: " + str(converted))
else:
         converted = weight * 0.45
         print(weight in Kgs: " +str(converted))
